
[1]invasion

   INVA'SION, n. s as z. [L. invasio, from invado. See Invade.]

   1. A hostile entrance into the possessions of another; particularly,
   the entrance of a hostile army into a country for the purpose of
   conquest or plunder, or the attack of a military force. The north of
   England and south of Scotland were for centuries subject to invasion,
   each from the other. The invasion of England by William the Norman, was
   in 1066.

   2. An attack on the rights of another; infringement or violation.

   3. Attack of a disease; as the invasion of the plague, in Egypt.
